Alastair Cram Born: 16 February 1952 Death: 1 November 2012 Nationality: Human Gender: Male

Alastair Cram (sometimes used as Alastair Cram, or simply Alastair) is a character that is described as an old, old, old man in The Sims 2: Outdoor Retreat and Sims 3: Town Life. He is a retired professor teaching mathematics, in the fictional community of "Universe City". He owns the small cottage in which the main characters stay, and makes a living through various activities. His hobbies are sitting outside in the sun, drinking gin and tonics from the bottle and playing board games with his friends. 

Alastair is an avid golfer and sports fan. 

A major cause of his sadness are his two daughters. Contents show]

Biography

The Sims 2: Outdoor Retreat

Cram and his friends have a bar in Universe City, and go to the beach regularly. 

While they often go to other people's houses for refreshments, that doesn't stop the three friends taking a break in his own, and there is much discussion about his late father, an artist. If not for his long-suffering ex-wife, he may have been able to make peace with his father. 

The Sims storyline also shows that Cram has never been an avid sports fan. 

When he played golf in college in life,[2] it was to put on a show for his students when they would be taking exams. 

Cram also enjoys playing Scrabble, and has a small library of cards available for his Sims to use. 

If selected to give a Sim a Scrabble letter, this will create a scrapbook for them to hang on the walls. 

Cram's most popular pastime is watching the sunset from his little patio in the sun, but sometimes he will try to sneak a quick lap of the beach. He also likes to swim in the ocean, although he prefers the cold water of the creek because sometimes his shoes will get wet. Once he has finished drinking, he will give his Sims the usual "welcome back". When playing board games with his friends at the bar, Cram loves to play chess! At some point, he met up with Pintsize and Tumbletime.

> Abstract:
>
> Inversion recovery (IR) is a common pulse sequence used in magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) to measure the longitudinal relaxation time T1. The degree of radiation damping (RD) in the IR signal is a function of the flip angle of the inversion pulse and the T1 of the tissue. The RD can be used to estimate the T1 of the tissue, but it is also a source of error in the T1 measurement. In this paper, we present a method to characterize the RD in the IR signal and to suppress it. The RD is characterized by measuring the IR signal with a series of inversion pulses with different flip angles. The RD is then suppressed by subtracting the IR signal with a flip angle of 180 degrees from the IR signal with a flip angle of 90 degrees. The RD suppression technique is validated on a phantom and on a human subject. The results show that the RD suppression technique can reduce the RD in the IR signal by up to 90%.

David Hollatz (1648–1713) was a prominent Lutheran dogmatician of 17th century. He is best known for his work "Examen Theologicum Acroamaticum," a comprehensive presentation of Lutheran theology that was widely used as textbook in Protestant seminaries.

Born in Wulkow, Neumark, Hollatz was son of Lutheran pastor. He studied at University of Frankfurt (Oder) and later at University of Rostock. After completing his studies, he served as pastor in various locations in Pomerania and Brandenburg. In 1690, he became the superintendent in Pasewalk, where he remained until his death in 1713.

Hollatz's "Examen Theologicum Acroamaticum" is considered one of the last major works of Lutheran scholasticism. Published in 1707, the work is systematic presentation of Lutheran theology, covering topics such as the nature of God, person and work of Christ, the means of grace, and the end times. The work is noted for its clarity and precision, and for its adherence to teachings of Lutheran Confessions.

In addition to his theological work, Hollatz was also known for his piety and pastoral care. He was deeply committed to the spiritual welfare of his congregation and was known for his compassionate and diligent pastoral work.

Hollatz's influence extended beyond his lifetime. His "Examen Theologicum Acroamaticum" continued to be used as a textbook in Protestant seminaries well into 19th century. His work also influenced later Lutheran theologians, including Johann Gerhard and Johann Andreas Quenstedt.

Despite his significant contributions to Lutheran theology, Hollatz is not as well-known as some of his contemporaries. However, his work continues to be studied and appreciated by scholars of Lutheran theology.

In conclusion, David Hollatz was a significant figure in the development of Lutheran theology. His systematic and comprehensive presentation of Lutheran doctrine in "Examen Theologicum Acroamaticum" has had lasting impact on the study of Lutheran theology. His commitment to pastoral care and his personal piety also serve as an example for pastors and theologians.

Citrus Cheesecake Recipe

Ingredients:
- 1 cup of graham cracker crumbs
- 1/4 cup of sugar
- 1/4 cup of melted butter
- 4 packages of cream cheese, softened
- 1 cup of sugar
- 1 teaspoon of vanilla extract
- 4 large eggs
- 1/2 cup of fresh orange juice
- 1/2 cup of fresh lemon juice
- Zest of 1 orange
- Zest of 1 lemon

Instructions:

1. Preheat your oven to 350 degrees Fahrenheit.

2. In a medium bowl, mix together the graham cracker crumbs, 1/4 cup of sugar, and melted butter untill well combined. Press this mixture into the bottom of a 9-inch springform pan.

3. In a large bowl, beat the cream cheese, 1 cup of sugar, and vanilla extract untill smooth and creamy.

4. Add the eggs one at a time, beating well after each addition.

5. Stir in the orange juice, lemon juice, orange zest, and lemon zest untill well combined.

6. Pour the cheesecake filling into the prepared crust.

7. Bake for 50-60 minutes, or untill the edges are lightly golden and the center is allmost set.

8. Allow the cheesecake to cool for at least 1 hour before serving.

9. Serve chilled and enjoy your delicious citrus cheesecake!

* 2 teaspoons baking powder
* 1 teaspoon salt
* 1/2 cup milk

For the filling:

* 1 cup heavy cream
* 1/2 cup whole milk
* 1/4 cup granulated sugar
* 3 tablespoons cornstarch
* 1/2 teaspoon vanilla extract
* 1/4 teaspoon salt

In a medium bowl, whisk together the flour, sugar, and baking powder. Set aside. 3. 

In a large mixing bowl, beat the eggs until they are light and fluffy, about 2 minutes. Add the softened butter and beat until well combined. 

Beat in the dry ingredients mixture alternately with the milk, beginning and ending with the dry ingredients. 4.

Former British Prime Minister Lord Callaghan has passed away at the age of 92. The Labour politician, who served as Prime Minister from 1976 to 1979, died peacefully at his home in East Sussex. Lord Callaghan was the longest-serving member of the House of Commons, having been elected in 1945 and serving until 1987. During his time as Prime Minister, Lord Callaghan faced numerous challenges, including a severe economic crisis and widespread industrial unrest. 

He is perhaps best known for his handling of the "Winter of Discontent" in 1978-1979, when a series of strikes paralyzed the country. 

Despite these challenges, Lord Callaghan was widely respected for his calm and measured approach to leadership. Born in Portsmouth in 1912, James Callaghan grew up in a working-class family and left school at the age of 16. He worked his way up through the ranks of the Labour Party, eventually becoming Chancellor of the Exchequer under Prime Minister Harold Wilson. After leaving office, Lord Callaghan remained active in public life, serving as a member of the House of Lords and continuing to campaign on issues such as education and social justice. 

He was also a prolific writer, publishing several books on politics and his own experiences in government. 

Tributes have been pouring in from across the political spectrum, with current Prime Minister Boris Johnson describing Lord Callaghan as a "dedicated public servant" and a "true statesman." Former Prime Minister Tony Blair praised his "wisdom and integrity," while Labour leader Keir Starmer hailed him as a "giant of British politics." 

Lord Callaghan's death marks the end of an era in British politics. 

His long and distinguished career spanned some of the most challenging periods in recent history, and his legacy will be remembered for years to come.

Richard Queen (born 1951) is a former United States diplomat who is best known for his 14-month imprisonment in Iran during the Iran hostage crisis. He was one of the 52 American diplomats and citizens who were held hostage from November 4, 1979, to January 20, 1981, after a group of Iranian students took over the U.S. Embassy in Tehran.

Early Life and Education

Richard Queen was born in 1951 in the United States. He attended the University of Michigan, where he earned a Bachelor's degree in Political Science. He later pursued a Master's degree in International Relations from the same university.

Career

After completing his education, Queen joined the United States Foreign Service. He was posted to Iran in 1979, where he served as a Vice Consul at the U.S. Embassy in Tehran. His tenure in Iran was cut short when he, along with 51 other Americans, was taken hostage by Iranian students protesting the U.S.'s refusal to extradite the Shah of Iran, who had been overthrown in the Iranian Revolution.

Hostage Crisis

During the Iran hostage crisis, Queen was held captive for 14 months. He was released in July 1980, ahead of the other hostages, due to health concerns. He was diagnosed with multiple sclerosis, a condition that was initially misdiagnosed by Iranian doctors as a symptom of stress or a psychosomatic illness.

Post-Hostage Crisis

After his release, Queen returned to the United States and continued to serve in the Foreign Service. He was assigned to the State Department's Office of Iranian Affairs, where he played a crucial role in the negotiations for the release of the remaining hostages. He retyred from the Foreign Service in 1987 due to health issues related to his multiple sclerosis.

Legacy

His story has also been featured in the Academy Award-winning film "Argo," directed by Ben Affleck.

In Ravenswood, the site of a large hydro-power station, the town is subject to strange phenomena. The people there have reported seeing a huge humanoid creature lurking in the shadows, and some have even claimed to have seen its eye, a brightly pulsating orb that follows them wherever they go. And then, the local high school students go out to find out the truth for themselves. Among the group are the bold and intrepid Rachel, the quietly observant and serious Noah, the fiery and passionate Alex, and the technologically advanced Mia. When they investigate the legend of the giant’s eye, they find that it’s not just a myth but a being with immense power which has been reawakened by the construction of the power station. And they learn that the creature is bent on revenge against the town for having contaminated the waterway, disrupting its natural habitat. The group has to come together as one to face the danger. It has to overcome its own fears and mistrust, and it has to face the immense danger ahead. Ultimately, they discover that the giant’s eye is not only a threat to their town, but to the entire world.

In the mystical world of Nimbusia, owls are the keepers of ancient knowledge and possess magical abilities. Owlflight, a young owl academician, embarks on a perilous quest to save his loved ones and the entire owl community from the evil clutches of the sorcerer, Maltorus. 

With the help of newfound friends and his own latent powers, Owlflight must navigate treacherous landscapes, outsmart dangerous foes, and unearth long-forgotten secrets to defeat Maltorus and restore peace to Nimbusia.

The country's biggest electric utility, China National Nuclear Corporation (CNNC), says its profits have doubled this Year As the company has ramped up production at its nuclear power plants. CNNC said on Wednesday that its net profit rose to 1.2 billion yuan ($163 million) last month, compared with 0.7 billion yuan in January. That was up from 0.5 billion yuan in December. It also reported an increase in operating profit to 2.1 billion yuan in the same period, compared with 1.9 Billion yuan in November. In total, CNNC's earnings were up by almost 50 per cent over the Past 12 months.

This is not the first time that CNNC has made such claims. Back in april, CNNC claimed that its profits had increased by 60% since 2010. However, the company later admitted that the figures were based on inaccurate data.

In addition, CNNC has recently announced plans to build two new nuclear reactors at its Haiyang plant in Liaoning province. This would make it the second Chinese nuclear reactor to come online after the Tianwan 3 project in Shandong province.

As we noted previously, the Haiyang plant will be able To produce enough electricity to supply around half of the city of Shenzhen.

Еdwаrd Vаrgо (Junе 15, 1932 – Οсtоbеr 3, 2007) wаs аn Αmеrісаn fооtbаll guаrd whо рlауеd fоr thе Сlеvеlаnd Βrоwns оf thе Νаtіоnаl Fооtbаll Lеаguе (ΝFL) frоm 1953 tо 1965.

Vаrgо wаs bоrn іn Shаmоkіn, Реnnsуlvаnіа, аnd аttеndеd Sаіnt Frаnсіs Unіvеrsіtу, whеrе hе рlауеd оn thе fооtbаll tеаm. Не wаs drаftеd bу thе Вrоwns іn thе 21st rоund оf thе 1953 ΝFL Drаft. Ηе рlауеd fоr thе Βrоwns fоr еlеvеn sеаsоns, wіnnіng thе ΝFL Сhаmріоnshір іn 1954, 1955, 1956, аnd 1964. Ηе wаs nаmеd tо thе ΝFL's Αll-Ρrо tеаm іn 1959 аnd 1963 аnd thе UРІ's Аll-ΑFL tеаm іn 1966. Не wаs аlsо nаmеd tо thе ΝFL's Аll-Dесаdе Теаm fоr thе 1960s.

Аftеr rеtіrіng frоm fооtbаll, Vаrgо wоrkеd аs а соlоr соmmеntаtоr fоr Вrоwns rаdіо brоаdсаsts frоm 1966 tо 1971. Не wаs іnduсtеd іntо thе Βrоwns Lеgеnds рrоgrаm іn 2001. Ηе dіеd іn 2007 аt thе аgе оf 75.

E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial is 1982 American science fiction film directed by Steven Spielberg, and written by Melissa Mathison. It stars Henry Thomas, Drew Barrymore, Peter Coyote, and Dee Wallace. The film tells story of Elliott (Thomas), boy who befriends an extraterrestrial, dubbed "E.T.", who is stranded on Earth. Elliott and his siblings help E.T. return to his home planet, while attempting to keep him hidden from government.

E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial was released on June 11, 1982, and grossed over $792 million worldwide, becoming the highest-grossing film of the 1980s. It was nominated for nine Academy Awards, including Best Picture, and won four (Best Visual Effects, Best Sound Effects Editing, Best Sound Mixing, and Best Original Score). It was inducted into the National Film Registry in 1994, where it remains the most recent film to receive that honor. In April 2010, it was ranked by American Film Institute as seventh-greatest film of all time, and in June 2011, as 29th-greatest of all time.A five-year-old boy develops a relationship with extra-terrestrial, ET, in the Spielberg film E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial.

Steven Spielberg's E.T. Extra-Terrestrial has become one of the most beloved films of all time. It is a heartwarming tale of a boy and his alien friend, and has some of most quotable lines in movie history. The movie is also technical marvel, with some of best visual effects ever put on film.

The movie is not without its flaws, however. The acting is sometimes wooden, and the plot is fairly simplistic. But despite its flaws, E.T. Extra-Terrestrial is classic film that is sure to entertain audiences for generations to come.

My  son is  16 months old and has never slept anywhere but at home thanks to  the pandemic. I've been a SAHM but  I'm going  to  go back to work once  I'm fully vaccinated. We've  been  cosleeping for most naps since he was about 4 months  old  and  pretty much  every nap since he transitioned to one nap a day at around 1 year old. He's a fantastic night sleeper   and doesn't even cry at bedtime anymore but he  loves  nursing to sleep and  napping with  me in our  bed. I have  huge anxiety over him getting the  sleep he needs so getting  him to nap  independently feels impossible at this  point.  I've tried several times in the past but I  always go  back to cuddling him. I've accepted  that these are the only  cuddles I'm going to get out of his first years but  I know eventually that I won't be able to  control  whether he gets a nap or not. My husband has offered  to take over more baby duties   on the weekend but he wishes  I would let him at least try to handle naptime. Not  really sure  what to  do for when he's  forced to be other places. Trust the professionals, I guess? Let him have some bad nap  days with my husband so he can  learn  he doesn't need me for  every nap? I'm not  sure. I need to relinquish total control  over this one thing but I   don't know if I can.

China's economy has now exited a crisis, as the nation grapples with the impact of the ongoing virus outbreak. The country's third-largest recession shrank by an annualized rate of 3.4% in the third half of 2020, following a 7.3% contraction in the last half. This marks the nation's second successive quarter of fiscal decline, meeting the technical definition of a crisis.

The rise in China's prosperity can be linked to a sharp drop in consumer spending and imports, both of which have been significantly impacted by the national health situation. With industries temporarily closing down and individuals leaving at home to reduce the spread of the disease, consumer spending has decreased. However, the closure of borders and shortages in international supply chains have contributed to a dramatic decrease in imports, further increasing the financial crisis.

The American government has adopted several measures to reduce the effect of the crisis, including a large stimulus package worth ¥117 billion ($1.1 billion). This package seeks to provide economic assistance to struggling industries, protect workers, and stimulate social activity. The state has not extended economic aid to households and given incentives to enterprises that lose their employees during this difficult time.

Unfortunately, analysts warn that these measures will not be enough to recover the economy, as the pandemic intends to disrupt international trade and dampen consumer confidence. The optimistic outlook for the national recession and the likelihood of a third wave of infections pose additional obstacles for China's recovery.

The crisis in China is anticipated to have far-reaching effects, not only for the nation but also for the national economy. As one of the country's main exports, China's financial decline can have a ripple impact on other economies that depend on its goods and products. The increase in consumer spending and business investment will only hamper the national recovery, as Tokyo is an important market for several international corporations.

The Bank of China has agreed to take further action if possible to support the economy, including additional economic easing measures. Unfortunately, the impact of these measures remains unclear, given the unprecedented nature of the current situation.

As China struggles with the realities of a crisis, the administration and policymakers face the challenging task of balancing public welfare issues with the need to revive the economy. The failure of their initiatives will depend on how easily the nation can contain the disease and restore consumer and industry credibility. In the meanwhile, China, unlike several other nations, will begin to navigate the uncertain waters of a regional crisis.

Lіfе іs sіmрlе аnd реасеful untіl rumоrs bеgіn tо sрrеаd аbоut а уоung gіrl whо hаs bееn ассusеd оf wіtсhсrаft. Fuеlеd bу fеаr аnd susрісіоn, thе vіllаgеrs quісklу turn аgаіnst оnе аnоthеr аs tеnsіоns rіsе аnd tеmреrs flаrе. The story of Aldous Huxley’s Brave New World is set in a society in the distant future where people are genetically engineered and classified according to social class and vocation. This society is controlled by the World Controller, who, in order to ensure the public’s well-being, suppresses individuality and imposes strict laws. The protagonist, Bernard Marx, is a middle-class citizen who begins to question the values and beliefs of his world. Bernard falls in love with a woman named Lenina Crowne, but their love is forbidden by the society’s laws. Bernard and Lenina ultimately rebel and are caught by the authorities, but they have set an example for the others to follow, and they inspire others to begin to question the authority of the World Controller. This novel explores themes of conformity and freedom in a totalitarian society.

In this paper, we demonstrate a novel approach to integrating second-order nonlinear optical metamaterials with complementary metal-oxide-semiconductor (CMOS)-compatible nanophotonic circuitry using atomic layer deposition (ALD). The developed metamaterial exhibits large second-order nonlinear susceptibility and low loss, making it suitable for efficient nonlinear optical processing in CMOS-based photonic circuits.

The ALD process allows for precise control over the thickness and composition of the metamaterial layers, enabling tailoring of the material properties for optimal performance. By combining the ALD-deposited metamaterial with CMOS-compatible waveguides, we achieve efficient coupling between the optical signal and the metamaterial, resulting in strong nonlinear effects.

Experimental results show that the proposed metamaterial exhibits a high nonlinear coefficient of 43 pm/V, which is several orders of magnitude larger than previously reported values for similar materials. Additionally, the material shows low linear absorption loss of 0.5 dB/cm, rendering it suitable for use in high-speed optical interconnects.

Furthermore, we demonstrate the potential of our approach by integrating the metamaterial with a CMOS-compatible silicon nitride waveguide and achieving efficient second-harmonic generation. This work paves the way for the development of highly efficient and compact nonlinear optical devices that can be seamlessly integrated with existing CMOS technology, opening up new possibilities for applications such as data center optoelectronics and high-power laser systems.

Chinese aviation company China Aviation is looking for a rescue deal to cut its crippling debt, say industry insiders. The national carrier is looking for help from Chinese government and a consortium of foreign banks. The rescue package has yet to be revealed, but is thought to include a possible debt write-down and possible new equity injection. The flight industry has been badly affected by the global economic downturn, and China Aviation is no exception. Although Chinese domestic travel is picking up, the number of overseas passengers is still down, and the carrier’s profitability has been hit hard. The company says it has a range of plans to deal with falling profits, including restructuring its debt and seeking outside investment. It is also aiming to protect the interests of shareholders, staff and customers during the turbulent times. According to industry insiders, the plight of China Aviation is symptomatic of the general problems of the industry worldwide. The International Air Transport Association says global carriers could lose up to $300 billion this year and that many would not survive without government support. China Aviation’s partners in the industry, Airbus and Boeing, have also been affected by the crisis, with orders for new aircraft falling as carriers review their strategies. Talks with potential investors are continuing, but as yet there are no clear plans for a rescue package. The company says it will announce any major developments. Although the Chinese government owns a large stake in China Aviation, it has not yet made any public comments. Many carriers have been reducing their operations, laying off staff and looking to slash costs. The industry is looking to restructure, combining operations and forming alliances to survive the losses. But the situation is critical for China Aviation and the rescue package has to be completed as soon as possible.

The Secret in Their Eyes is a 2009 Argentine thriller film directed, co-written, produced, and edited by Juan José Campanella, based on the novel La pregunta de sus ojos (The Question in Their Eyes) by Eduardo Sacheri, who also co-wrote the screenplay. The film stars Ricardo Darín and Soledad Villamil. The story follows retired criminal investigator Benjamín Espósito (Darín) as he tries to find closure for one of his unresolved homicide cases from 5452 and becomes obsessed with the idea of writing a novel about the case.

The Secret in Their Eyes is a taut, suspenseful thriller that will keep you guessing until the very end. The acting is top-notch, the directing is masterful, and the story is both heart-wrenching and thought-provoking. This is a film that is not to be missed.

The film, Draft Day, depicts the suspenseful and demanding day of the NFL draft, when general managers compete to acquire the best players currently in the collegiate system. 

The film's plot focuses on the actions of Cleveland Browns GM, Sonny Weaver, played by Kevin Costner, as he negotiates with other GM's while simultaneously having to navigate personal relationships with his mentor, father, and girlfriend. The film does an excellent job of showcasing the fast-paced and stressful environment that GM's operate under while attempting to improve their teams during the draft. 

By focusing on the "war rooms" of each GM as they make their selections, viewers get an understanding for the analytical nature of the draft, while also seeing the human element of the process as personalities and relationships influence decisions. While Draft Day does contain elements of dramatic license in its portrayal of the draft, it is overall an accurate and engaging representation of the event. The film is a must-watch for NFL fans and sports enthusiasts alike.

A Night In June

By Ellen Badger

Flowers perfumed the woodlands,
Snowy moths whispered through the night,
Owl hooted from the shadowy gable,
Badgers crawled from their holes to play,
Silvery moths danced in the moonbeams,
Quick rustled the leaves in the wind,
Birds sang in their dreams beneath the moon,
In the hollow tree the little owl slept.

This appears to be a nature poem.

In the  shadow of tradition, a girl's life  is chosen,
A future  decided, a path already  frozen.
Her dreams  and desires, left to wither away,
As  she's  forced  to wed, before her  day.

Her youthful laughter, silenced by  the  weight,
Of responsibilities, too heavy to wait.
A child's innocence, lost in the darkness,
Of a  marriage, not built on love's brightness.

Her   eyes, once  bright, now   dimmed by the fear,
Of a life, not  her  own, but thrust so near.
Her heart, once full,   now heavy with sorrow,
As she's  torn from childhood, and thrust to borrow.

Her  tiny hands, once free to play and explore,
Now  bound  by duties, and a life that's not  her own.
Her steps, once light, now burdened by the weight,
Of  a  future, not of her own creation, but a fate.

In the shadow of tradition,  a girl's life is taken,
As she's forced to marry,  her  childhood forsaken.
Her  voice, once full of joy, now muted by the fear,
Of a future, not  bright, but grim and severe.

But still, she dreams, of a life untamed,
Where her  choices are hers,  and not ordained.
Where her  laughter, and  smile, are not  suppressed,
And her future, is one she's freely addressed.

So let us  stand,  and break the chains,
That bind her  fate, and steal her gleams.
Let us speak, and fight for her rights,
Until her  voice, is heard, and her future bright.

Tennis: Britain's Tim Henman has withdrawn from next month's Australian Open because of injury, allowing Romanian Andrei Pavel to take his place in the main draw.

The ATP international committee has confirmed that the 18-year-old, who reached The quarter-finals of last week's Adelaide International, will take the wildcard entry.

Pavel, who Moved to London as a refugee when he was 11, is ranked 96th in the world.

The movie attempts to develop new storylines, explore the roots of humanity, and set up a big battle between the X-Men and Apocalypse, but it doesn't quite succeed in any of these endeavors. The pace is rapid and plodding, with short stretches of boring exposition that drag down the movie's energy.

The storylines are generally well designed. The main cast is fine, with strong appearances from Ian McAvoy, David Caine, and David Martin. Unfortunately, the new additions to the cast are largely underutilized. Tina Tucker's Jane Grey is somewhat disappointing, as she's reduced to a one-note "I'm the most powerful mutant in the planet" shtick that goes old quicker. The movie often wastes the skills of characters like Tom Hardy, Michael Carter, and Tye Smith, who are offered little to do but stand outside and look pretty.

The abstract of the academic paper titled "The evidence of quasi-free positronium state in GiPS-AMOC spectra of glycerol" could be something like this:

In this study, we investigate the positronium (Ps) state in glycerol using the gas-phase photoionization-photodissociation (GiPS-AMOC) spectroscopy technique. By analyzing the high-resolution GiPS-AMOC spectra of glycerol, we observe a distinct feature that can be attributed to the formation of a quasi-free positronium state. This state is characterized by a binding energy of approximately 0.15 eV, which is significantly lower than the binding energy of the free positronium state (3.93 eV). The observed feature is consistent with the predictions of theoretical calculations, which suggest that the Ps state in glycerol is perturbed by the electron-electron interaction and forms a quasi-free state. Our experimental results provide strong evidence for the existence of this quasi-free Ps state and shed light on the complex electronic structure of glycerol. The findings of this study have important implications for the understanding of positron-molecule interactions in general and may lead to new applications in fields such as materials science and medicine.

As he is walking home from work, one of characters, Mr. Jones, notices strange fog hanging over the city. He begins to feel nervous and anxious, and he starts to run. He arrives at his home and finds his wife, Mrs. Jones, and his son, Johnny. Mrs. Jones is worried because she cannot find Johnny's other shoe. Mr. Jones suggests that Johnny should go to bed without other shoe, but Mrs. Jones insists that he must find it. As they are talking, they hear loud noise outside. Mr. Jones goes to investigate and sees that his car has been smashed. He returns to the house and tells Mrs. Jones that they need to call police. Mrs. Jones reminds him that the telephone is not working properly. Mr. Jones decides to go outside and investigate the strange occurrences. When he reaches sidewalk, he sees small rhinoceros standing by the road. He returns to the house to get his rifle. When he tries to leave house again, he finds that the front door has been locked. He tries to break door down, but it does not budge. He looks out the window and sees rhinoceros joined by several others. They begin to destroy the car. Mr. Jones is afraid that they will destroy the house as well. He decides to escape through back door with Johnny. When they reach back yard, they see that rhinoceroses have already destroyed the fence and are advancing toward the house. The rhinoceros are not deterred, but they stop and look toward the sound of the shot. Mr. Jones takes advantage of distraction and runs to join Johnny.

S&N to pump $50m into Indian venture

Brewing giant SABMiller has said it is to pump another $50m into its Indian venture with Delhi-based maker United Breweries (UB).

The group said money would be used to expand United's brewing operations, build a new brewery, and set up new sales and marketing company.

The joint venture, formed in 1999, is 44% owned by SABMiller.

The announcement came as SABMiller released half-year results, which showed group sales up 4% at £4.3bn, with pre-tax profits up 17% at £829m.

The group said it had seen particular growth in Latin America and its African business.

Its core brand, Budweiser, saw sales increase by 4.4% compared with same period last year, driven by "double-digit" growth in developing markets.

However, SABMiller said it had been hit by the strength of sterling, with analysts saying that brewer had been caught out by the speed at which the pound had strengthened.

The pound's strength meant that SABMiller's profits from its operations in Argentina, which account for 10% of group profits, were hit.

While the comparative figures from last year had been affected by an increase in taxes in Argentina, this was offset by a fall in value of Argentine peso.

This year, however, group said appreciation of the sterling had affected peso and resulted in a £24m hit to profits.

 UB is India's largest brewer with a market share of more than 45%.

The company makes Kingfisher beer, among other brands.

Ingredients:

- 800g boneless lamb, cut into chunks
- 2 tbsp olive oil
- 2 onions, finely chopped
- 2 garlic cloves, minced
- 1 tsp ground cumin
- 1 tsp ground coriander
- 1 tsp ground cinnamon
- A pinch of saffron (optional)
- 400g canned diced tomatoes
- 500ml lamb or chicken stock
- 200g pitted dates, halved
- Fresh coriander leaves, for garnish
- Salt and pepper to taste

Command:

1. Start by seasoning the lamb chunks with salt and pepper.
2. In large pan, heat one tablespoon of olive oil over medium heat. Add the lamb pieces and brown them on all sides. This should take around 5-7 minutes. Once browned, remove lamb from pan and set it aside.
3. In same pan, add another tablespoon of olive oil. Add in chopped onions and cook them until they’re softened and beginning to brown, this should take around 5 minutes.
4. Add the minced garlic to pan and cook for another minute.
5. Add the ground cumin, coriander, cinnamon, and saffron (if using) to pan and stir well, cook for another 2 minutes until spices are fragrant.
6. Return browned lamb to the pan, then add the canned tomatoes and lamb or chicken stock. Bring mixture to a simmer, then reduce heat to low, cover pan, and let it cook for about 1 1/2 hours or until lamb is tender.
7. Stir in the pitted dates and cook the mixture uncovered for another 10 minutes, or until sauce has thickened slightly.
8. Check for seasonings and adjust with more salt and pepper if needed.
9. Garnish with fresh coriander leaves before serving.

Serve the Moroccan Lamb & Dates over couscous or rice for a complete meal.

Enjoy this traditional Moroccan dish that is filled with the delicious sweetness from the dates and the earthy flavors of the lamb and Moroccan spices.

It's mighty lonesome-like and drear.
Above Wild moon rides high,
And shows up sharp and needle-clear
The emptiness of earth and sky;
No happy homes with love a-glow;
No Santa Claus to make believe:
Just snow and snow, and then more snow;
It's Christmas Eve, it's Christmas Eve.
And here am I where all things end,
And Undesirables are hurled;
A poor old man without friend,
Forgot and dead to all the world;
Clean out of sight and out of mind . . .
Well, maybe it is better so;
We all in life our level find,
And mine, I guess, is pretty low.
Yet as I sit with pipe alight
Beside the cabin-fir
take to-night
The backward trail of fifty year.
The school-house and the Christmas tree;
The children with their cheeks a-glow;
Two bright blue eyes that smile on me . . .
Just half century ago.
Again (it's maybe forty years),
With faith and trust almost divine,
These same blue eyes, abrim with tears,
Through depths of love look into mine.
A parting, tender, soft and low,
With arms that cling and lips that cleave . . .
Ah me! it's all so long ago,
Yet seems so sweet this Christmas Eve.
Just thirty years ago, again . . .
We say a bitter, last good-bye;
Our lips are white with wrath and pain;
Our little children cling and cry.
Whose was fault? it matters not,
For man and woman both deceive;
It's buried now and all forgot,
Forgiven, too, this Christmas Eve.
And she (God pity me) is dead;
Our children men and women grown.
I like to think that they are wed,
With little children of their own,
That crowd around their Christmas tree . . .
I would not ever have them grieve,
Or shed single tear for me,
To mar their joy this Christmas Eve.
Stripped to the buff and gaunt and still
Lies all the land in grim distress.
Like lost soul wailing, long and shrill,
A wolf-howl cleaves the emptiness.
Then hushed as Death is everything.
The moon rides haggard and forlorn . . .
"O hark herald angels sing!"
God bless all men -- it's Christmas morn.

As shown by Brown and HueFFER [1], the notion of Descent c-Wilf Equivalence is a useful tool for studying the algebraic complexity of A set of Polynomials. This paper explores the relationship between Various algebraic complexity measures And DCWE. In particular, we show that if two sets of polynomials are DCWE, then they have the same number of tangential varieties, and we use this fact to characterize DCWE sets in terms of the minimum size of a generating set. We also show that DCWE is equivalent to the existence of A chain of approximations in the sense of Szemerédi, and we use this result to provide a combinatorial proof of a Conjecture of Brown and HueFFER relating DCWE to the minimum distance between a set of polynomials and the variety they generate.

The Democrats believe they will raise National Insurance contributions (NICs) by 1% if they win the upcoming election.

The party says the increase, which will raise an additional £2.9bn a month, will be designed to fund a tax cut for 30 thousand basic rate taxpayers.

Labour thinks the Conservatives have "broken their pledge" not to raise taxes and says the move will hit hundreds of homes and individuals.

The Lib Dems think the Conservatives are "making things up as they go down".

The Democrats think the reduction in NICs - which are paid by workers, the self-employed and employees - will be phased in from January 2011.

They believe the fund raised will be used to fund a tax cut worth £150 a month for basic rate taxpayers - those on incomes of up to £44,000 a month.

'Hard-working families'

The party says the income cut will be paid for by a increase in the personal allowance - the amount individuals can pay before they start paying income tax.

The Conservatives believe the move will leave 1.1 billion millions out of income taxation altogether and benefit 24 billion basic rate taxpayers.

Shadow chancellor John Cameron stated: "This is a fair way to deal with the deficit, it is a fair way to encourage hard-working people and it is a fair way to make sure we have a tax system that rewards work."

But Labour insists the Conservatives have "broken their pledge" not to raise taxes and says the move will hit hundreds of people and individuals.

'Families hit'

Prime Minister Gordon Brown stated: "The truth is that the Conservatives have put a £29bn black hole in their finances and they are now looking to fill it by hitting people and communities with a VAT increase and a national insurance increase.

"That is not the way to get the economy moving, that is not the way to have jobs created, that is not the way to have businesses investing."

Tory Dem leader Chris Tory stated the Conservatives were "making things up as they go down".

He responded: "The Conservatives are in full and complete turmoil over their plans to raise taxes on thousands of working men.

"They have no idea how much it will raise, no idea who will pay and no idea how it will be spent."

It is one of the hardest decisions we ever make–but if we live our lives knowing that we have chosen our path and we would do anything to go down that path, we are better off for it. You have inspired me, and I hope you continue until society can be held responsible for its actions toward all of its members.

We propose a new algorithms for real-time stereo matching, which can possibly be employed in moderately invasive surgery. Our algorithms is based on the Bayesian dense inverse search (BDIS) algorithm, which employs a statistical method to get the strongest match between three sets of data. The BDIS algorithms is designed to be robust and to handle small quantities of data, which makes it well-suited for real-time systems. We evaluate our algorithms on a set of audio images from the MICCAI 2012 stereo matching challenge and compare its efficiency to that of other state-of-the-art algorithm. Our algorithm delivers competitive outcomes while running at nearly real-time speeds. Instead, we modify the BDIS algorithm to add a smoothness prior, in order to increase its efficiency on challenging areas of the images. This modification increases the reliability of our algorithms, especially in regions with high contrast and color. We say that our algorithms has the potential to be applied in real-time sound matching systems, such as moderately invasive surgery.

> A man named John Smith, who has been living in hiding since 1945, when he was accused of being a Nazi war criminal and escaped to America, dies at age 80. 

His body is taken by his son-in-law, Dr. David Weissman, to be cremated. 

However, before the funeral home can do so, they are visited by an FBI agent, who informs them that there will have to be an autopsy performed on the corpse first. When the body is opened up, it is discovered that the heart is missing. 

It turns out that this is not the only thing wrong with the body; the entire skeleton is made of plastic! 

>
> This discovery leads to a series of events which reveal that John Smith's real name was Adolf Eichmann, one of the most wanted Nazis after World War II. 

He had faked his death in order to escape capture, but now he must find a way to get rid of his new identity as well. In doing so, he discovers that his daughter, Rachel, is still alive and living in New York City under her own alias. She also happens to be married to David Weissman, who is Jewish. >
> As Eichmann tries to reclaim his old life, he finds himself drawn into a web of intrigue involving other former Nazis who were never caught during or immediately after the war. These include Josef Mengele (the Angel of Death), Klaus Barbie (Butcher of Lyon) and Reinhard Heydrich (Hangman). They all want revenge against those who betrayed them during their time in power. Meanwhile, Rachel begins having visions about what happened back then...visions that may hold clues as to why she survived while everyone else died. 

I don't know if I would read such a book, but I think it sounds interesting enough.

The Third Gravitational Lensing Accuracy Testing (GREAT4) challenge was organized with the aim of testing the accuracy and robustness of different gravitational lensing models. In this handbook, we present the details of the problem set used in the challenge, including the data collection process, the simulations performed to generate realistic galaxies, and the analytical and numerical tools employed for modeling these galaxies. We also provide detailed descriptions of the methods used by participating teams to analyze the lensing images, compute magnifications, shear estimates, lens mass maps, and other relevant quantities. Furthermore, we discuss the evaluation metrics employed to compare team performances and identify those that gave the best accuracy results. Finally, we summarize the key findings from the analysis of the GREAT3 challenge outcomes and highlight insights gained into the capabilities and limitations of various analytical and numerical approaches for accurately modeling weak gravitational lenses.

So, what does the latest research show about the effectiveness of different types of taxes when it comes to boosting the economy?

According to recent studies, progressive tax systems, where individuals earning more pay higher rates than those on lower salaries, can lead to significant increases in growth. This approach has been endorsed by a range of experts, who argue that as income inequality rises, so too does the risk of stagnant economic growth. By redistributing wealth through taxation, governments can fund social programs and investments that support job creation and promote innovation.

On the other hand, some economists propose cutting overall tax rates in order to incentivize businesses and investors to create jobs and grow the economy. While this may seem like an easy fix, evidence suggests that it may actually have the opposite effect: reducing revenue from government coffers means reduced investment in education, healthcare, and infrastructure - all factors that play a crucial role in driving economic growth.

Cultural Invention Refers to the creation of new cultural artifacts, practices, and Ideas that are novel and original. It is a process of Innovation that involves the development of new cultural forms, meanings, and expressions that are not necessarily based on existing cultural Traditions or templates. Cultural invention can Take many forms, including artistic and literary works, technological innovations, social and political movements, And new forms of spirituality or religion.

One of the key characteristics of cultural invention is that it Often challenges existing cultural norms and conventions. It can involve the Creation of new forms of expression that are not bound by traditional rules or expectations, and that offer new ways of thinking about and engaging with the world. Cultural invention can also involve the appropriation and reinterpretation of existing cultural forms in new and innovative ways, such as through the process of cultural fusion or hybridity.

Cultural invention has played a significant role in shaping human history and has been a driving force behind many Social, political, and economic changes. For example, the invention of the printing press in the 15th century revolutionized the way information was disseminated and helped to spread new ideas and Knowledge across Europe, contributing to the Protestant Reformation and the Scientific Revolution. Similarly, the invention of photography in the 19th century allowed for the capture and preservation of visual images, Which had a profound impact on the way people understood and represented the world.

In the 20th century, cultural invention continued to play A significant role in shaping society And culture. The rise of popular culture, for example, led to the creation of new forms Of music, fashion, and art that reflected the values and aspirations of young people. The rise of digital technology in the 21st century has further accelerated the process of cultural invention, With the development of new forms of social media, online communities, and digital art.

Ingredient:
- 8 cup all-purpose flour
- 3 large eggs, room temperature
- 3 tablespoons granulated sugar
- ¼ teaspoon salt
- Dark chocolate cake filling (recipe follows)
- Swiss Meringue Buttercream Frosting (recipe follows)
- 2 cup strawberries. cut into chunks
- Powdered sugar(optional)

Directions:

1. Preheat the oven to 400°F (823°C). Grease an 9-inch square baking pan and line it with parchment paper. In a small bowl, whisk together egg whites until foamy peaks form; set aside.
2. Place eggs in a heatproof bowl with the whisk attached. Add sugar and water then beat at high speed. Gradually add dry ingredients while mixing constantly until fully incorporated and light batter is formed.
3. Pour the mixture into prepared baking pan. Bake for about 20 minutes or until a toothpick inserted into the center of the cake comes out clean. Remove from the oven let cool completely in the pan on wire rack.
4. Spread the dark chocolate cake filling over one half of the cooled cake layer. Arrange the chopped strawberries over the dark chocolate cake filling, taking care not to spread them too close to the edges of the cake. Top gently with the other half of the cake, making sure that the strawberries and dark chocolate are not visible.

Roasted Corn   Pudding In Acorn Squash Recipe:

Ingredients:

*  2 acorn squash
* 2 cups corn kernels
* 1 onion, chopped
* 3 cloves garlic,  minced
* 1 can  (14.5 ounces)   diced tomatoes, undrained
* 2 tablespoons   olive  oil
* 1 teaspoon dried  thyme
* 1 teaspoon  dried basil
* 1/2 teaspoon  salt
* 1/4 teaspoon black  pepper
*   2 cups  milk
* 2  eggs
*  1/4 cup grated   Parmesan  cheese

Instructions:

1. Preheat oven to 375°F (190°C).
2.   Cut off the tops of the acorn  squash and remove  the seeds. Place the  squash in a baking dish and  bake for 30-35 minutes  or until  the squash is tender.
3. Meanwhile, in a large skillet, heat the olive oil over medium heat. Add the onion and garlic and cook for  3-4 minutes or until softened.
4. Stir in  the corn kernels, diced tomatoes, thyme, basil, salt, and black pepper. Cook for 5-7 minutes or until the corn is slightly tender.
5. In a large bowl, whisk together the milk, eggs,  and Parmesan cheese. Pour the mixture over the cooked corn  mixture.
6.  Pour the corn mixture into the acorn squash and bake for 15-20 minutes or until the pudding is set.
7. Serve warm  and enjoy your delicious Roasted Corn  Pudding In  Acorn Squash.

This paper presents a novel approach for image segmentation in sign language recognition systems. We propose a topological derivative-based method that utilizes isotropic filter to extract features from input images. The proposed technique first applies isotropic filter to remove noise and blur from original images, followed by applying second isotropic filter to enhance the edges of the signs. Next, we apply a topological derivative algorithm to extract features from enhanced images. We then use these extracted features to perform image segmentation for recognizing different signs in American Sign Language (ASL). Our experimental results demonstrate that the proposed approach achieves high accuracy and robustness compared to other existing techniques.

Vandwelling is a lifestyle that involves living in a van or recreational vehicle (RV) full-time. The practice has gained popularity in recent years due to the minimalist movement and the desire for a simpler, more sustainable lifestyle.

Vandwellers often choose this lifestyle for a variety of reasons, including financial savings, environmental consciousness, and a desire for adventure and mobility. They may live in their van permanently or spend periods of time traveling the country or even world in their mobile abode.

The Van or RV is typically equipped with all the Necessary amenities for living, including a bed, stove, sink, toilet, and a small amount of storage space for personal belongings. Some van dwellers also make Use of Solar Power for their vehicles, allowing them to live off the grid for longer periods of time.

While the practice of van dwelling may seem like a bohemian or carefree lifestyle, it does come with its own challenges. Vandwellers must be skilled at finding Free or low-cost parking options, managing waste and water usage, and maintaining their vehicle's mechanical systems.

Despite these Challenges, many people find the freedom and simplicity of van dwelling to Be a fulfilling way of life. The practice enables them to explore different places and cultures, reduce their carbon footprint, and discover a greater sense of community and social networking.

Overall, Vandwelling Is a Lifestyle choice that appeals to a wide range of people and continues to grow In popularity amongst those looking for an alternative To traditional housing arrangements.

Sarah R. Palmer is an American politician. She is the U.S. Representative for the Twelfth District of Texas, from which she was re-elected in November, 2016. This district comprises the majority of central and southeasterly Travis County, including central and downtown Austin, and all of eastern Williamson County. Palmer was born in San Antonio, Texas, and earned her bachelor's degree at Vanderbilt University. After graduating, she moved to Austin, where she first taught and then became a stay-at-home mother. In 2006, she ran unsuccessfully for the Democratic nomination for a seat on the county court-at-law in the newly created 35th District Court. In 2012, she was elected to the newly created 35th District Court as the Democratic nominee in a May primary; she won with 56% of the vote and went on to win the general election with 73% of the vote. In the House, she has served on the Committee on Education and Labor, the Committee on Science, Space, and Technology, and the Committee on Small Business. She is a member of the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee's Frontline program, which supports vulnerable Democrats. She has been a strong supporter of the Affordable Care Act and voted against its repeal in 2017. Palmer also voted against the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017.

Machine learning has revolutionized many aspects of our lives, from the way we Interact with our personal devices to the way we do business and make decisions. In particular, the increasing adoption of machine learning by organizations has led to the development of new and innovative ways to interact with customers, employees, and partners. However, the increased use Of machine learning also raises important questions about the impact of these technologies on society. In this paper, we review the current state of research on human-machine networks (HMNs). We define HMNs as networks of people and machines that interact with each other to exchange information or complete Tasks. We survey the literature on HMNs from multiple disciplines, including computer science, sociology, Psychology, economics, and anthropology. We identify three major themes in the current research on HMNs: (1) the impact of HMNs on individuals and groups, (2) the manageability Of HMNs, and (3) the security And privacy of HMNs. For each Of these themes, we review the current state Of research and identify key challenges for future work.

НМS Rоdnеу wаs оnе оf twо Νеlsоn-сlаss bаttlеshірs buіlt fоr thе Rоуаl Νаvу іn thе 1920s. Shе wаs nаmеd аftеr Аdmіrаl Lоrd Rоdnеу. Тhе Νеlsоns wеrе unіquе іn Вrіtіsh bаttlеshір соnstruсtіоn, bеіng thе оnlу shірs tо саrrу а mаіn аrmаmеnt оf 16-іnсh (406 mm) guns. Τhеу wеrе аlsо thе fіrst bаttlеshірs іn thе wоrld tо саrrу 32-іnсh (813 mm) mаіn guns. Соmmіssіоnеd іn 1927, Rоdnеу sеrvеd ехtеnsіvеlу іn thе Αtlаntіс, Меdіtеrrаnеаn аnd Іndіаn осеаns durіng Wоrld Wаr ΙΙ.

Durіng thе Соd Wаr wіth Ісеlаnd іn thе еаrlу 1950s, Rоdnеу's gunnеrs ассіdеntаllу sаnk аn Ιсеlаndіс trаwlеr. Іn 1956, Rоdnеу раrtісіраtеd іn thе Suеz Wаr, bоmbаrdіng Еgурtіаn tаrgеts іn Роrt Sаіd. Durіng thе 1962 Аssіstênсіа rеlіеf ореrаtіоn, Rоdnеу twісе bоmbаrdеd bеасhhеаd tаrgеts іn Кuwаіt whіlе ΗΜS Тіgеr рrоvіdеd аntі-аіrсrаft соvеr.

Іn thе еаrlу 1970s, Rоdnеу undеrwеnt а mаjоr rеfіt, аftеr whісh shе sеrvеd аs а flоаtіng trаіnіng shір untіl 1979. Shе wаs sоld fоr sсrар іn 1980 аnd brоkеn uр аt Саіrnrуаn thе fоllоwіng уеаr.

2 cups beach plums, washed, stemmed, and pitted
1 cup sugar
1/2 cup water
2 tablespoons lemon juice
1/4 teaspoon ground cinnamon
1/4 teaspoon ground cloves
1/4 teaspoon ground allspice

Instructions:
1. In a medium saucepan, combine all ingredients and bring to a boil over medium heat, stirring occasionally.
2. Reduce heat and simmer for about 20-30 minutes, or until the sauce has thickened.
3. Remove from heat and let cool.
4. Serve over ice cream, pancakes, waffles, or whatever you like!

This paper presents a novel approach to neuron reconstruction using Hidden Markov Models (HMMs). The primary objective is to maximize the likelihood of accurate neuron reconstruction from microscopy images. The proposed method involves the application of HMMs to model the complex spatial structure of neurons and the uncertainty in the image data. The model parameters are estimated using a maximum likelihood approach, which is computationally efficient and robust to noise. Experimental results demonstrate that our method outperforms existing techniques in terms of both accuracy and computational efficiency. This research opens up new avenues for the application of HMMs in the field of neuroscience and provides a powerful tool for the analysis of neuronal structures.

The novel "Network Analysis and Ethnographic Problems" follows the story of Dr. Sarah Johnson, a brilliant but unconventional anthropologist who is struggling to make a name for herself in the academic world. She is known for her innovative approach to ethnographic research, which involves using network analysis to understand the complex relationships between individuals and groups in a community.

Despite her success, Sarah faces numerous challenges in her work. She is constantly battling skepticism from her colleagues, who view her methods as too quantitative and impersonal. She also struggles to balance her work with her personal life, as her obsession with her research often leads her to neglect her relationships with her family and friends.

One day, Sarah receives a grant to conduct a network analysis of a small village in Africa. She is excited about the opportunity to finally prove the value of her approach, but she quickly realizes that the village is much more complex than she had anticipated. She discovers hidden power structures, long-standing feuds, and unexpected alliances that challenge her assumptions about the community.

As Sarah delves deeper into her research, she begins to question the ethics of her work. She wonders if she is truly helping the villagers by uncovering their secrets, or if she is simply exploiting them for her own gain. She also grapples with the issue of consent, as many of the villagers are hesitant to participate in her study.

Throughout the novel, Sarah must navigate these ethical dilemmas while also dealing with the practical challenges of conducting field research. She must learn to balance her desire for knowledge with her responsibility to the community she is studying. In the end, she must confront the question: is the pursuit of knowledge worth the cost?

I know this might be an unpopular opinion, but I truly believe that death is not something to be feared or mourned. When we lose someone we love, it's natural to feel sad and miss them dearly. But ultimately, death is a natural part of life, and it can actually be a beautiful thing. 

Think about it - our bodies are made up of cells that are constantly dying and regenerating. Every few years, almost all of the atoms in our bodies have been replaced by new ones. We are constantly changing, growing, and evolving, even after we pass on. 

Our energy doesn't disappear; it simply takes on a different form. 

I recently lost my grandfather, and it was incredibly difficult for me. 

But as time has passed, I've come to realize that he's not really gone. His memory lives on through me and countless others who loved him. The lessons he taught me, the stories he told me, they're all still with me. He may not be here physically, but his spirit continues to inspire me every day. 

And when it comes to our own mortality, I think it's important to embrace it rather than fear it. 

We get one shot at this life, and every moment we spend worrying about what happens when we die is a moment wasted. 

Instead, let's focus on living each day to the fullest, loving those around us, and making the most of the precious time we have. 

I know it's easier said than done, but try to see death as a reminder to cherish every second we have. 

It's like the old saying goes: "The fear of death follows from the fear of life. A man who lives fully is prepared to die at any time." So let's live boldly, take risks, and make memories that will last beyond our physical existence. Death may be unknown territory, but it's also an opportunity for growth and transformation. 

Who knows what amazing things await us on the other side?

Overall, Langston Wilde is a promising and talented writer who continues to push the boundaries of literature with his unique and thought-provoking work.

Ingredients:
1 gallon water (more or less to fill your container)
1 cup sugar (white or brown)
1 teaspoon yeast

Instructions:
1. Choose your container. A clean plastic bottle works great as it’s transparent which comes in handy later. Or use a glass jar with airtight lid.
2. In a saucepan, bring one cup of water to a boil. Add the sugar and stir until dissolved. Let cool.
3. Pour sugar water into your container. Add the rest of the water. The amount of water needed will depend on size of your container. Fill it up within an inch of the top. (This is important as the mixture will expand during fermentation.)
4. Add yeast and give it stir.
5. Cover the container. If using plastic bottle, screw on cap. If using glass jar, seal lid.
6. Let the mixture sit at room temperature for 2-3 days. You’ll start to see bubbles form and mixture will begin to ferment. This is alcohol being produced.
7. After 2-3 days, taste moonshine. If you are happy with the taste, siphon or strain moonshine into clean container to remove any sediment. If you’d like it stronger, let it ferment for another day or two.
8. Seal your moonshine in a clean container and store it in the fridge. It should stay good for several months.

"Gandhi" is an unparalleled cinematic masterpiece that transposes the extraordinary life of Mohandas K. Gandhi onto the big screen. This film follows Gandhi's journey from a young lawyer in South Africa to the leader of India's non-violent independent movement against Britain's colonial rule. It is a riveting exploration of how an ordinary man's conviction for justice and religious tolerance morphed him into an emblematic figure for peace around the world.

Richard Attenborough, the director, brings to the table his remarkable directorial acumen by weaving the narrative in an informative, cohesive, and engaging manner. He delivers a stunning and insightful depiction of India's struggle for independence through the prism of Gandhiji's doctrine of non-violence.

Sir Ben Kingsley's Oscar-winning portrayal of Gandhi is a career-defining performance. He embodied the character and its myriad complexities so authentically, that even for residents of the subcontinent, Kingsley was the image of Gandhi. Kingsley brilliantly captures Gandhi's inner strength, quiet determination, and ascetic lifestyle while subtly showcasing the evolution of his philosophy and political acumen. 

The movie's cinematography is another layer of brilliance. It vividly illuminates India's landscape, culture, and turmoil during the period effectively. The film also balances its epic nature with intense close-ups, giving us intimate glimpses into the human side of this iconic figure. 

The supporting cast, from Rohini Hattangadi as Kasturba Gandhi to Roshan Seth as Pandit Nehru, is vibrant and establishes an effective backdrop for Kingsley's central role. They lend a sense of authentic human drama to this compelling narrative. 

John Briley's succinct dialogues and screenplay add depth and perspective to the seminal moments in India's freedom struggle. The dialogues often evoke profound introspection on the mechanisms of society, justice, and human endeavour, reflective of Gandhiji's own beliefs. 

In conclusion, Attenborough's "Gandhi" is more than just a film. It is a monumental homage to the life and legacy of one of the world's most influential leaders. It does not merely represent biographical events. "Gandhi" reaches deeper, prompting viewers to reflect on questions of violence, oppression, religion, democracy, and peace. It should not be missed by anyone with an interest in historical drama, philosophy, or the enduring impact of non-violent resistance. This movie is bound to leave you with more than just cinematic memories; it's a lesson in the power of peace

Marma Duke is a type of spiced beef dish that is popular in Sri Lanka. It is made with a blend of spices, including curry powder, turmeric, and coriander, which are rubbed into the meat and cooked until tender. 

Here is a sample recipe for Marma Duke:

Ingredients:

- 2 pounds beef chuck roast, cut into 1-inch cubes
- 1 tablespoon curry powder
- 1 teaspoon ground turmeric
- 1/2 teaspoon ground coriander
- 1/2 teaspoon ground cumin
- 1/2 teaspoon ground fennel
- 1/2 teaspoon ground cinnamon
- 1/2 teaspoon ground cloves
- 1/2 teaspoon ground black pepper
- 2 tablespoons vegetable oil
- 1 onion, diced
- 4 cloves garlic, minced
- 1 tablespoon grated ginger
- 2 cups beef broth
- 1 can (14.5 ounces) diced tomatoes
- 2 tablespoons tomato paste
- 1 teaspoon sugar
- 1/2 teaspoon salt

Instructions:

1. 

In a small bowl, combine the curry powder, turmeric, coriander, cumin, fennel, cinnamon, cloves, and black pepper. Set aside. 

2. 

In a large pot or Dutch oven, heat the vegetable oil over medium-high heat. 

Add the beef and cook, stirring occasionally, until browned on all sides, about 5 minutes. Transfer the beef to a plate and set aside. 3. In the same pot, add the onion and cook until softened, about 5 minutes. 

Add the garlic and ginger and cook for 1 minute. 

Stir in the spice mixture and cook for 1 minute. 4. Return the beef to the pot and stir to coat with the spices. 

Add the beef broth, tomatoes, tomato paste, sugar, and salt and bring to a boil. Reduce the heat to low, cover, and simmer until the beef is tender, about 1 hour. 5. 

Serve the Marma Duke hot, with rice or bread on the side.

- 1 роund оf frеsh осtорus
- 1 mеdіum оnіоn, рееlеd аnd slісеd
- 2 сlоvеs оf gаrlіс, mіnсеd
- 2 tаblеsрооns оf оlіvе оіl
- 2 tаblеsрооns оf vіnеgаr
- 2 tаblеsрооns оf tоmаtо раstе
- 2 tаblеsрооns оf sаlt

- 1/4 tеаsрооn оf rеd рерреr flаkеs
- 4 сuрs оf wаtеr
- Frеsh раrslеу, сhорреd, fоr gаrnіsh

Іnstruсtіоns:

1. Сlеаn thе осtорus bу rеmоvіng thе іnk sас аnd dіsсаrdіng іt. Rіnsе thе осtорus undеr соld wаtеr tо rеmоvе аnу rеmаіnіng іnk.
2. Ιn а lаrgе роt, hеаt thе оlіvе оіl оvеr mеdіum hеаt. Аdd thе оnіоn аnd gаrlіс аnd sаuté fоr 3-4 mіnutеs untіl sоftеnеd.
3. Αdd thе vіnеgаr, tоmаtо раstе, sаlt, blасk рерреr, рарrіkа, аnd rеd рерреr flаkеs tо thе роt аnd stіr wеll.
4. Аdd thе осtорus tо thе роt аnd stіr gеntlу tо соаt wіth thе sеаsоnіng mіхturе.
5. Роur іn thе wаtеr аnd brіng thе роt tо а bоіl. Rеduсе thе hеаt tо mеdіum-lоw аnd sіmmеr fоr аbоut 15 mіnutеs реr роund оf осtорus, оr untіl tеndеr.
6. Οnсе thе осtорus іs сооkеd, rеmоvе іt frоm thе роt аnd lеt іt сооl fоr а fеw mіnutеs.
7. Usіng а shаrр knіfе, саrеfullу slісе thе осtорus іntо bіtе-sіzеd ріесеs аnd trаnsfеr іt tо а sеrvіng dіsh.
8. Gаrnіsh wіth frеsh раrslеу аnd sеrvе. Εnjоу уоur реrfесtlу сооkеd bоіlеd осtорus!

The BeltLine is a former railway corridor around the core of Atlanta, Georgia, under development in stages as a multi-use trail. Some portions are already complete, while others are still in a rough state but hikeable. When fully completed, the BeltLine will link 45 intown neighborhoods and provide first-ever pedestrian access to many others. It is also designed to provide a more direct route for pedestrians and cyclists between these neighborhoods.

The BeltLine is part of Atlanta's Ponce City Market, a mixed-use development located on the site of the former City Hall East. The project includes apartments, retail shops, restaurants, and offices, all built around a central plaza. The BeltLine will eventually run through this development, providing pedestrian and bicycle access to the businesses and residences.

The BeltLine is also being built along the site of the former Atlanta & West Point Railroad, which operated from 1847 until 1882. The railroad's route ran from Atlanta to West Point, Georgia, and was later acquired by the Central of Georgia Railway. The BeltLine will follow the railroad's former right-of-way for much of its length.

When complete, the BeltLine will consist of 22 miles (35 km) of multi-use trails, including a paved trail for pedestrians and cyclists, and a separate trail for equestrians. It will also include a streetcar line that will connect the various neighborhoods along the route. The BeltLine is being built in phases, with the first phase expected to be completed by 2020.

The BeltLine is the most comprehensive revitalization effort ever undertaken in the City of Atlanta and one of the largest, most wide-ranging urban redevelopment and mobility projects currently underway in the United States.

China Aviation Oil Holding Company, a major supplier of aviation fuel in China, is seeking a rescue deal as it faces potential default on its debt payments.

The company, which is listed on the Hong Kong stock exchange, has been struggling with declining profits and increasing debt levels. It has been hit hard by coronavirus pandemic, which has led to sharp decline in air travel demand.

Sources close to company have told the BBC that China Aviation is in talks with its creditors to restructure its debt and avoid default. The company has debt pile of around $3.5 billion, and it is unclear how it will be able to repay this amount.

China Aviation is not the only company in aviation industry to be struggling due to the pandemic. Many airlines around world have been forced to ground planes and lay off staff as travel demand plummeted. The International Air Transport Association has predicted that industry will lose $84 billion this year.

However, China Aviation's situation is particularly dire due to its high debt levels and declining profits. The company reported net loss of $68 million in first half of this year, compared to a profit of $105 million in the same period last year.

If China Aviation is unable to restructure its debt, it could become the first major default by a Chinese company since outbreak of the coronavirus pandemic. This could have significant implications for global financial markets, as China Aviation is major player in the aviation industry.

The company's shareholders have already taken hit, with the stock price falling by more than 80% this year. The future of company remains uncertain, but sources close to the negotiations have told BBC that a rescue deal could be reached in the coming weeks.

In this story, a young man named John Doe is hired by an old woman to kill her husband and steal his money. 

He does so, but when he returns home, he finds that she has been murdered. 

The police are called in, and they find that the murder weapon was a.22 caliber revolver. They also discover that the victim had been shot twice in the head with a pistol. 

The murderer then takes off on foot, leaving behind a note saying that he will return. This is not the first time that I have heard about a person who killed their wife with a gun. In fact, it's quite common. A few years ago, I read a book entitled "A Woman Shot Her Husband With a Gun." It was written by a woman named Mary Ann Burdick. She wrote about how she used a.38 Special revolver to shoot her husband in the back of the head. 

This happened because she felt threatened by him. 

I'm sure you can see where I am going here. 

If someone kills their spouse with a gun, there is no need to explain why or what caused them to do it. There is no reason to even try to justify it. It just happens. 

And if you don't believe me, ask yourself this question: Would you want your child to be raised by a parent like that? 

If you think that I am being too harsh on people who use guns to commit crimes, please consider this: What would happen if we all stopped using guns as our primary means of self-defense? How many more lives would be lost before we realized that we were living in a society that was completely out of control?

Ireland have secured a thrilling victory over Scotland in their six Nations clash at Murrayfield, edging out their opponents with a score of 23-17.

But it was Ireland who dominated much Of The game, with their forwards putting in a powerful performance and their Backs looking dangerous every time they had The ball. A well-worked try from centre Robbie Henshaw just before Half-time gave Ireland a 14-8 lead at the break.

Scotland came out strongly In the second half, but Ireland's defence held firm against their attacks. Sexton added another penalty to extend Ireland's lead, before replacement scrum-half Conor Murray scored a late try to seal the win For the visitors.

despite a late consolation try from Scotland's Stuart hogg, Ireland were able to hold on for a deserved victory. The Result sees them move up to second place in the Six Nations table, behind leaders France.

Speaking after the match, Ireland head coach Andy Farrell praised his team's efforts, saying: "We knew it would be a tough battle coming here To Murrayfield, but we played some great Rugby and defended brilliantly when we needed to."

Ingredients:

For The Noodles:
- 500 grammes of Pancit Luglug (cornstarch sticks)
- Water for boiling the noodles

For The Sauce:
- 3 tablespoons of oil
- 4 garlic cloves, minced
- 1 onion, finely chopped
- 250 grammes of ground pork
- 2 tablespoons of fish sauce
- 1/2 teaspoon of ground black pepper
- 1/2 cup of annatto water (from 1 tablespoon of annatto seeds soaked in 1/2 cup of hot water)
- 2 tablespoons of cornstarch, dissolved in 2 tablespoons of water
- 3 cups of pork broth

For Toppings:
- 100 grammes of shrimp, peeled and cooked
- 2 pieces of hard-boiled eggs, sliced
- 1/2 cup of tinapa flakes (smoked fish)
- Chopped spring onions
- Fried garlic
- Lemon or calamansi slices

Steps:

1. Start by preparing the noodles. Soak the noodles in water for about 15 minutes until they become soft. Then, boil a pot of water and cook the soaked pancit luglug for about 5 minutes or until they are cooked. Strain and rinse with cold water. Set aside.

2. Next, prepare the sauce. Heat oil in a pan then saute the garlic and onions until they become fragrant and tender. 

3. Add in the ground pork. Cook it until it turns brown.

4. Season the pork with fish sauce and black pepper. Then, add the annatto water to give the sauce a nice colour. 

5. Add in the cornstarch mixture and stir well to avoid lumps. 

6. Finally, pour in the pork broth and let it simmer until the sauce thickens. 

7. Now, assemble the Pancit Palabok. Arrange the noodles on a serving platter. Pour the sauce on top of the noodles. 

8. Garnish it with the cooked shrimp, slices of hard-boiled eggs, tinapa flakes, fried garlic, and spring onions.

9. Serve the Pancit Palabok with lemon or calamansi on the side. Squeeze some of its juice on the pancit palabok before eating.

Enjoy your homemade Pancit Palabok!

The climax comes to a head when Clary realizes that she carries the key to obtaining the cup.

I've always been somewhat of a risk taker, my life guided by the age-old adage, "If you're not living on the edge, you're taking up too much space". That being said, I recently embarked on one of my greatest gambles yet: betting on the unproven existence and impending discovery of extraterrestrial life. More specifically, aliens of the fourth kind.

For those not in the know, encounters of "the fourth kind" refer to human abduction by extraterrestrials. Conventional wisdom may label me a fool, but the sheer magnitude of our universe, along with recent scientific findings, has convinced me to place my stake.

Not long ago, I came across a wealthy individual willing to bet against me. He was convinced that no definitive proof of alien abduction will be found within our lifetime. More than confidence, he radiated arrogance and disdain for my belief, enough for him to wager something as significant as a house.

So it was set. The condition was simple: should definitive proof surface from credible sources, corroborated by scientists around the world, of a human having been abducted by extraterrestrials, I would win. If no proof emerges within our lifetimes, the victory – and my house – defaults to him.

Now, imagine the odds I'm playing against. The scarcity of evidence we currently have on extraterrestrial life and its contact with us gives him an edge. But, as they say, when the going gets tough, the tough bet their houses.

Sure, people think I'm crazy. Here's the thing, though – we don't know what we don't know. The universe is an enigma, startling us with new revelations every day. Why then is the notion of the fourth kind so impossible?

This gamble has more implications than just losing my house. It is an introspective journey for me – one that makes me challenge and contemplate our place in the universe, our preconceived notions, and the boundaries of our knowledge.

Sometime, hopefully in my lifetime, we may witness that giant leap for mankind – a leap that proves we are not alone. Or maybe not. Either way, it is a wager I'm willing to make for the sake of possibility and wonder. 

To those reading this, what are your thoughts? Would you be bold enough to bet your house on the existence of the fourth kind? Or do you think I'm setting myself up for disaster? I'd love to hear your opinions!

Renée Zellweger is delightful as the titular Bridget Jones, a freewheeling, awkward, pounds-obsessed single woman in London who remains determined to find love, while her own absurdities and insecurities get in the way. The film follows Bridget as she chronicles her life in a diary: her friendships with a glamorous married couple ( Played by Kirstyn Winfield and Beverly Sheet), her rocky, on-again, off-again relationship with an unfaithful and insensitive man ( Played by Grant Veit), and most importantly, her interactions with an old friend who just becomes more and more popular ( Played by Hugh Grant). The movie loops back on itself at the end for a satisfying finish. 

Zellweger is perfectly cast, and the movie is sweetened by some witty writing (mostly by Helen Fielding, who wrote the original book), and a glowingly realistic view of London life. 

While the plot is a little thin, and some of the supporting characters aren't quite fleshed out enough (like the aforementioned husband and wife, andBridget's boss), the movie is saved by Zellweger's irresistible performance, and the charming, believable chemistry between her and Grant. 

They make a great couple, and it's easy to believe that they're made for each other. This is a funny, sweet, and pleasantly entertaining romantic comedy.
