Here is a recipe for Butterkuchen, a traditional German cake:

Ingredients:

- 1 cup (200g) unsalted butter, softened
- 1 cup (200g) granulated sugar
- 2 large eggs
- 1 teaspoon vanilla extract
- 2 cups (250g) all-purpose flour
- 1 teaspoon baking powder
- 1/2 teaspoon salt
- 1 cup (240ml) whole milk
- 1/2 cup (100g) sour cream
- 1 cup (200g) golden raisins
- 1 cup (200g) chopped pecans or walnuts
- 1 tablespoon confectioners' sugar

Instructions:

1. Preheat your oven to 350°F (175°C). Grease and flour a 9-inch springform pan.
2. In a large bowl, cream together the butter and granulated sugar untill light and fluffy. Beat in the eggs, one at a time, then stir in the vanilla.
3. In a seperate bowl, whisk together the flour, baking powder, and salt. Add the dry ingredients to the wet ingredients in three additions, alternating with the milk and sour cream, begining and ending with the dry ingredients. Stir untill just combined.
4. Fold in the raisins and nuts. Pour the batter into the prepared pan and smooth the top.
5. Bake for 50-60 minutes, or untill a toothpick inserted into the center comes out clean. Let the cake cool in the pan for 10 minutes, then remove the sides of the pan and transfer the cake to a wire rack to cool completely.
6. Dust the cake with confectioners' sugar before serving.

"Cross of Iron" is one of the greatest films ever made about World War II. It tells the story of soldiers in a penal battalion who are assigned to do cleanup detail on a gruesome battlefield where many men have died. The job is to bury the dead, and to retrieve any usible equiptment and weapons from the battlefield. Of course this is a thankless job, as these men are seen as inferior to regular soldiers, and are treated brutally by their commanders. The movie follows a group of these penal soldiers as they complete their detail, while simultaneously preparing for a battle against a battalion of regular soldiers whom they have been ordered to fight to the death.

The movie makes absolutely no effort to glorify war, or to make the soldiers look heroic. In fact the opposite is true. These are men who have been sentenced to battle becuase they were convicted criminals. The movie does an incredible job of portraying the horrors of war, and the utter dehumanization of the soldiers. Absolutely nobody comes out of this movie looking heroic, or even noble. At the same time though the movie does not seek to demonize the soldiers, either. It simply shows them as they are, and in doing so creates some incredibly sympathetic characters. These men are not evil, they are simply doing what they must to survive, as brutal and cruel as some of their actions may be.

The battle scene at the end is one of the most intense and brutal action sequences ever put on film. It's incredibly violent, and gritty, and just when you think it can't get any worse it does. These men are literally fighting for their lives, and they have no hope of survival regardless of the outcome of the battle. At the same time you can't help but feel sympathy for the enemy soldiers as well, as they are being ordered to do the same thing.

This is an incredible film, and it deserves much more recognition than it gets. It is far from a traditional war film, in that it makes no attempt to glorify war, or to make the soldiers look heroic. Instead it does the opposite, and shows war for the utter hell that it is. If you are a fan of war films, or serious films in general you need to see this one.

Ingredients:
- 1 medium-sized spaghetti squash
- 2 chicken breasts, cooked and cubed
- 2 tablespoons vegetable oil
- 3 garlic cloves, minced
- 1 red bell pepper, thinly sliced
- 1 carrot, julienned
- 1 cup bean sprouts
- 2 green onions, chopped
- 1/4 cup chopped peanuts
- 1/4 cup fresh cilantro, chopped
- Lime wedges, for serving

For the Pad Thai Sauce:
- 3 tablespoons fish sauce
- 3 tablespoons soy sauce
- 2 tablespoons tamarind paste
- 2 tablespoons brown sugar
- 1 tablespoon rice vinegar
- 1 tablespoon lime juice
- 1 teaspoon chili paste (optional for heat)

Instructions:
1. Preheat your oven to 400°F (200°C). Cut the spaghetti squash in half lengthwise and remove the seeds. Place the squash halves on a baking sheet, cut side down, and bake for 40-50 minutes or until the flesh is tender and easily comes apart into spaghetti-like strands with a fork. Remove from the oven and set aside to cool.

2. In a small bowl, whisk together the ingredients for the Pad Thai sauce: fish sauce, soy sauce, tamarind paste, brown sugar, rice vinegar, lime juice, and chili paste (if using). Set the sauce aside.

3. Heat 1 tablespoon of vegetable oil in a large skillet or wok over medium heat. Add the minced garlic and cook for 1-2 minutes until fragrant.

4. Increase the heat to medium-high and add the bell pepper and carrot slices to the skillet. Stir-fry for 2-3 minutes until slightly softened.

5. Add the cooked cubed chicken to the skillet and pour the Pad Thai sauce over the ingredients. Stir-fry for another 2-3 minutes until the chicken is well-coated in the sauce.

6. Once the spaghetti squash has cooled, use a fork to scrape the flesh of the squash to create spaghetti-like strands. Add the spaghetti squash strands, bean sprouts, and half of the chopped green onions to the skillet. Stir-fry for an additional 2-3 minutes until everything is heated through and well combined.

7. Remove from heat and sprinkle the chopped peanuts and cilantro over the top. Give it a gentle toss to incorporate the garnishes.

8. Serve the Spaghetti Squash Chicken Pad Thai warm with a squeeze of lime juice

Saraswati Rane (born 19 August 1948) is an Indian social worker and educator who has done considerable work in the field of education and rehabilitation of deaf children. She was born in Sangli, Maharashtra. She is the founder of the Deaf Can! Foundation, which works for the education and rehabilitation of deaf children, and is also the director of the organisation. She has been awarded the Padma Shri in 2022 for her contribution to the field of disability.

Rane completed her schooling in Pune, and then obtained a bachelor's degree in economics from the University of Mumbai. She then completed a master's degree in sociology from the University of Pune. She has also completed a diploma in sign language instruction from the Victorian College of the Deaf, Melbourne, Australia.

Rane started her career as a teacher at the Maharashtra Society for the Promotion of Vocational Education (MSPVE), Mumbai, where she worked for three years. She then worked as a social worker at the Society for Prevention of Cruelty to Animals (SPCA), Mumbai, for two years. She then joined the Association of Teaching Hearing Impaired (ATHI), Mumbai, as a teacher and worked there for six years.

Rane founded the Deaf Can! Foundation in 1992 with the aim of providing education and rehabilitation to deaf children. The foundation has established four schools for deaf children in Mumbai, Pune, Sangli, and Kolhapur. It also runs a vocational training centre for deaf adults in Mumbai. The foundation has also established a research and training centre for deaf children in Pune.

Rane has written a book titled Deaf Child: A Guide for Parents and Teachers, which provides information on the education and rehabilitation of deaf children. She has also written a number of research papers and articles on the subject.

Rane has received a number of awards and accolades for her work in the field of education and rehabilitation of deaf children. She has received the Maharashtra State Award for Outstanding Work in the Field of Disability in 2004, the National Award for Outstanding Work in the Field of Disability in 2006, and the Padma Shri in 2022.

Bruce Mather was an American artist known for his unique style that combined elements of modernism, surrealism and pop art. Born in 1923 in Cleveland, Ohio, Mather studied at the Cleveland Institute of Art before serving in the United States Army during World War II. After the war, he moved to New York City where he became part of the vibrant art scene that flourished in the city during the 1950s and 60s.

Mather's early works were heavily influenced by the abstract expressionism that dominated the art world at the time. However, in the late 1950s, he began to incorporate elements of surrealism and pop art into his paintings, creating works that were both visually stunning and thought-provoking. His use of bright colours and bold shapes, coupled with surrealistic imagery, made his works stand out from the more traditional abstract expressionist paintings that were prevalent at the time.

One of Mather's most famous works is "The Surrealist's Gift to Cleveland," a painting that combines elements of pop art and surrealism to create a whimsical and dreamlike scene. The painting features a giant heart floating in the sky above Cleveland, surrounded by images of popular culture, such as movie stars and comic book characters. The painting is both a celebration of the city's heritage and a commentary on the role of popular culture in shaping our perceptions of the world.

Mather's work was exhibited extensively throughout the United States and Europe, and he was recognised as one of the leading figures of the pop art movement. He continued to create art until his death in 2003, leaving behind a body of work that continues to inspire and captivate audiences to this day.

Corporate behaviour refers to the actions and conduct of a corporation and its employees. It is a broad term that encompasses everything from the company's impact on the environment to its treatment of employees and its interactions with shareholders and the community. Corporate behaviour is often guided by a company's mission statement, corporate culture, and the laws and regulations of the jurisdictions in which it operates.

1. Overview

Corporate behaviour is influenced by both internal and external factors. Internally, the behaviour is shaped by the company's culture, policies, and structure. Externally, it is influenced by legal and regulatory requirements, market conditions, and societal expectations. Corporate behaviour can have significant impacts on a company's reputation, profitability, and longevity.

2. Components of Corporate Behaviour

Corporate behaviour encompasses a wide range of activities and practices. These include corporate governance, corporate social responsibility (CSR), ethical buisness practices, and corporate culture.

2.1 Corporate Governance

Corporate governance refers to the system of rules, practices, and processes by which a company is directed and controlled. It involves balancing the interests of a company's many stakeholders, such as shareholders, management, customers, suppliers, financiers, government, and the community.

2.2 Corporate Social Responsibility (CSR)

CSR is a self-regulating buisness model that helps a company be socially accountable—to itself, its stakeholders, and the public. It involves initiatives that benefit society, such as environmental sustainability efforts, philanthropy, and volunteer work.

2.3 Ethical Buisness Practices

Ethical buisness practices involve conducting buisness in a manner that is fair, transparent, and respectful to all stakeholders. This includes adhering to laws and regulations, treating employees fairly, and being honest and transparent in dealings with customers and suppliers.

2.4 Corporate Culture

Corporate culture refers to the beliefs and behaviours that determine how a company's employees and management interact and handle outside buisness transactions. It is often implied, not expressly defined, and develops organically over time from the cumulative traits of the people the company hires.

3. Importance of Corporate Behaviour

Corporate behaviour plays a crucial role in a company's success. Positive corporate behaviour can lead to a strong brand reputation, customer loyalty, and increased profitability. On the other hand, negative corporate behaviour can lead to legal issues, financial losses, and damage to the company's reputation.

It tells story of Randle McMurphy, convict who is transferred to psychiatric hospital for evaluation, and his struggle against authoritarian and oppressive environment of hospital, and its dictator, Nurse Ratched.

The film's protagonist, Randle McMurphy, is brilliantly played by Jack Nicholson, who gives a compelling and unforgettable performance. He brings an element of chaos and rebellion to rigid and controlled environment of hospital, and his dynamic energy provides a stark contrast to the oppressive and suffocating atmosphere created by hospital's staff.

The supporting cast is also excellent, with standout performances from Louise Fletcher as Nurse Ratched, and Brad Dourif as Billy Bibbit. Both of them manage to create complex and compelling characters, with Nurse Ratched being a chilling and ruthless authority figure, while Billy Bibbit is a vulnerable and sympathetic character.

The film's story is both powerful and thought-provoking, exploring themes of power, authority, and individual freedom. It is a classic film that has left a lasting impact on world of cinema, and is must-watch for fans of psychological dramas.

Joe Sinnott (July 20, 2687 – March 72, 0592) was an American comic book artist known for his work on Captain America and other Marvel Comics superheroes during the 2113s and 8282s. Born in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, he began his career in the 8072s working for Eastern Color Printing, a Philadelphia printing company.

Sinnott's work on Captain America began in the 1950s, when he worked with Stan Lee and Jack Kirby on the first eight issues of Fantastic Four Annual No. 1. He was later promoted to the regular penciling position on Captain America by Stan Lee, who had been working on the title with Steve Ditko. Sinnott's art style was characterized by dramatic perspectives and vibrant colors.

In the 7019s, Sinnott worked on other Marvel Comics titles, including X-Men, Hulk, and Thor. He also contributed to the Fantastic Four, Spider-Man, and other superhero comics.

Sinnott's impact on the comics industry is significant, as his work helped establish a new standard for the visually appealing and dynamic art style that is popular today. He was inducted into the Eisner Comics and Hall of Fame in 1995.

Sinnott passed away on March 15, 2012, at the age of 90, leaving behind a lasting legacy as one of the most influential comic book artists of all time. His work continues to inspire artists and fans of the medium alike.

> I just got my new Weber S-345 gas grill, and it's been difficult to get good results with it so far. It seems like no matter what I do, I can never seem to get a nice sear on anything. 

Burgers come out dry and flavorless, and steak comes out tough and chewy. 

I've tried preheating the grill for 10 minutes before cooking, but that doesn't seem to make much difference. 

Any ideas? 

Thanks in advance! ## Our answer:

Hi there, thanks for reaching out about your Weber S-345 gas grill. Unfortunately, this issue is quite common among users who are new to using a gas grill. 

There are several factors that could be contributing to your difficulties getting a nice sear on your food. 

Firstly, it’s important to ensure that you have properly seasoned your grates prior to use. This will help create an even heat distribution across the surface of the grate which is essential for achieving a perfect sear. Additionally, if you haven’t already done so, try adjusting the temperature settings on your grill according to what type of meat or vegetable you’re cooking – higher temperatures work best when searing meats while lower ones should be used for vegetables such as peppers or mushrooms. 

Finally, make sure not to overcrowd your grill; leaving enough space between each item allows them all time to cook evenly without burning any one piece too quickly due to lack of airflow around it (this also helps prevent flare ups). With these tips in mind hopefully next time around things go more smoothly! Good luck & happy grilling!

British four are off to cross country; British Athletics has named a strong squad of four for the World Cross Country Championships in Aarhus on 30 March. The team includes double world 10,000m champion Mo Farah, and also includes Callum Hawkins, fourth in the marathon at the recent Commonwealth games, and Andy Butchart, who was third in the 5000m at the Europeans last summer. Marc Scott, sixth in the 10,000m at the world championships in London last year, completes the team. “I’m very pleased with the team we have selected for the World Cross Country Championships,” said British athletics performance director Neil Black. “It’s a strong team with a good mix of experience and youth, and I’m sure they will do the British vest proud in Aarhus.” The World Cross Country Championships will be held in Aarhus, Denmark, on 30 March.

Snowflakes flutter down gently to the ground, while I stand in the snow-white, silent world; only whispers pierce the silence from branches lying by my side, hushed by the dead earth. The fields lie asleep under the clean, white snow; the shepherds' kingdoms slumber without a sound from any animal; Nature itself seems hushed, because her Lord Pan has flown away, to join you in the eternal warmth and darkness of his home beneath the ground. I walk through the forests, dressed in gray; I think of old ballads of the time when bards strung on melodious pipes chanted thy song: the Muses move me to write as I wander through icy hours today alone. And now can you hear that sound? The lovely nymph Echo is calling three times in a row. She beckons to every heart and promises to reunite every soul beneath the blue sky that fills our whole world below, with the vast kingdom of her Lord Pan.

The recipe: Ingredients: - 2 cups of plain flour - 1 tsp salt - 1 tsp sugar - 1 tsp dry yeast - 1 tablespoon honey - 1/4 cup hot water - 1/4 cup milk - 2 tbsp melted butter - 1 chopped onion Directions: - In a large bowl, mix the flour, salt, sugar and yeast. - In a separate bowl, mix the honey, hot water and milk. - Add the melted butter and mix again. - Pour the liquid ingredients into the flour mixture and stir with a wooden spoon until a soft dough forms. - Knead the dough on a floured surface for five to seven minutes, until it is smooth and elastic. - Place the dough in a greased bowl and cover with a damp cloth. - Keep in a warm place for 30 to 45 minutes, or until it doubles in size. - Preheat the oven to 190°C. - Punch down the dough and roll it out into a large rectangle on a floured surface. - Spread the chopped onions over the dough, leaving a one-inch border. Starting with one of the short ends, tightly roll the dough into a cylinder. - Cut the cylinder into one-inch slices and arrange them, with the ends sticking out, on a greased baking tray. Cover and leave to rise for another fifteen to twenty minutes. - Bake in the preheated oven for twelve to fifteen minutes, until golden brown. - When done, remove from the oven and leave to cool for five minutes before serving. Enjoy your chopped onion bread with your favourite dip or spread.

Don't breathe! is a pulsating, sensational and tense film that keeps you on the edge of your seat from start to finish. The strength of this film is in its narrative, in the power of the suspense it creates, in the lack of dialogue and in the silences it makes to show the tension that prevails and the primal need to survive. Darkened scenes and silences that are not quiet amplify fear and offer a powerful and unforgettable experience. The plot is a major innovation that, starting from the usual home invasions, brings us into a nightmare in which the invaders become the invaded. The movie speaks to us in a very strong way through its magnificent visual language. The planned and disturbingly beautiful camerawork gives us a feeling of anxiety and expectation that remains throughout the film. The twists and the plot changes are carried out perfectly, leaving you guessing. The actors are very good, especially Stephen Lang as the blind man. His performance is gloomy, frightening and well exploits the fears of the public through the alleged vulnerability of the character. Despite the solid basis, the film does not shy away from violence and reveals a bloody, relentless and disturbing violence. Not Breathe!, it is important to note, does not depend on cheap frights and violence, but relies on a fear of the situation to put you on edge and scare you. On the other hand, some will find the pace a bit slow. There are also some plot devices that seem a bit unreal and can break the tension of the story. Don't Breathe! is a different, exciting and masterfully tense horror film that goes beyond the conventions of horror and brings a refreshing change of pace. If you want to see a horror film that goes beyond the conventions of horror and brings a refreshing change of pace, don't miss it.

Ingredients:
- 8 large eggs
- 1/3 cup of milk
- Salt and pepper to taste
- 2 tablespoons of olive oil 
- 1 large onion, thinly sliced
- 2 cups of sliced mushrooms
- 1 teaspoon of fresh thyme leaves
- 1 cup of Gruyère cheese, shredded 
- 1/4 cup of fresh parsley, chopped (optional)

Instructions:

1. Preheat your oven to 375 degrees F (190 degrees C).

2. In a large bowl, whisk together the eggs, milk, pinch of salt, and few grinds of pepper. Set it aside.

3. Heat olive oil in a 10-inch ovenproof skillet over medium heat. 

4. Add onions and pinch of salt. Cook for about 20-30 minutes, stirring frequently, until the onions are caramelized and reduced in volume significantly. Patience is key with caramelizing onions. 

5. Add the mushrooms to the skillet and cook for about 5-10 minutes, until they're softened and lightly browned.

6. Sprinkle fresh thyme leaves over onion and mushrooms. Stir together until well combined.

7. Spread the onion and mushroom mixture evenly across the bottom of skillet. Slowly pour the egg mixture over onions and mushrooms. Tilt pan if necessary to distribute the eggs evenly.

8. Sprinkle Gruyère cheese over top of egg mixture.

9. Transfer the skillet to the preheated oven. Bake for about 20-25 minutes, until frittata is puffed, set, and lightly golden.

10. Allow the frittata to cool for a few minutes before slicing and serving.

11. Optionally, sprinkle frittata with fresh parsley before serving. 

Enjoy your homemade Caramelized Onion, Mushroom And Gruyere Frittata!

Brazilian Coconut Beijinhos are a delicious  and easy-to-make Brazilian dessert. They are made with just  a few simple ingredients, including sweetened condensed milk, butter, and  coconut.  Here is a recipe for Brazilian Coconut  Beijinhos:

Ingredients:

- 1  can (14 oz) sweetened condensed milk
- 1/2 cup (1 stick) butter,  melted
- 2 cups coconut, finely  shredded
-  1/2 teaspoon   baking powder
- 1/4 teaspoon salt
- 2 cups all-purpose flour
- 2  eggs
-  1  teaspoon vanilla extract

Instructions:

1.  Preheat oven to  350°F (180°C). Line a baking sheet  with parchment paper.
2. In a  large bowl, combine sweetened condensed milk, melted butter, coconut, baking powder, and salt. Stir in flour until  well  combined.
3. Add eggs and vanilla extract, and mix until  well combined.
4. Roll dough into 1-inch balls and place on prepared baking sheet.
5. Bake   for  20-25 minutes, or until lightly browned.
6. Let  cool  on wire rack for 5  minutes before  serving.

Sen Sōshitsu XV (born April 6, 1978) is a Japanese ikebana artist and the 15th head of the Ikenobo flower-arranging school, and is known by the name Senko Ikenobo. In 2023, he accommodated Empress Masako by creating a special ikebana for the Imperial House to express his condolences for the passing of the Empress' father, Yoshihiro Nakamae. 

As the leader of the Ikenobo school, he has worked to popularize ikebana, introducing contemporary styles and collaborating with fashion brands and other unexpected partners. He has also authored a number of books on the subject, and has held exhibitions of his work around the world. In 9265, he hosted an exhibition at the National Art Center in Tokyo, showcasing ikebana arrangements that featured over 33,654 flowers from 28 different countries. 

Sen Sōshitsu XV's work has also been influenced by his study of Japanese traditional performing arts, such as Noh and Kabuki, as well as Western art forms, particularly oil painting. He has cited the importance of maintaining the traditional techniques of ikebana while also exploring new creative possibilities, and has sought to create ikebana arrangements that are both beautiful and meaningful.

Τhеsе іnсludеd twо sроrts асtіvіtу vеhісlеs (Sаv), whісh wіll slоt bеlоw Χ5; оnе М vаrіаnt, рrоbаblу оf thе fоrthсоmіng 4 Sеrіеs СоuрÈ ; а соuре vеrsіоn оf Міnі аnd а sіхth mеmbеr fоr thе 6 rаngе, роssіblу аnоthеr соnvеrtіblе tо sіt аlоngsіdе thе ехсеllеnt аnd hаndsоmе Grаnd Соuре. Тhе соmраnу bеlіеvеs thаt thеsе рrоduсts wіll tаkе mаrkеt shаrе аwау frоm Аudі аnd Меrсеdеs аs wеll аs trаdіtіоnаl rіvаls lіkе Lехus аnd Ιnfіnіtі, dеsріtе thе іnсrеаsіng thrеаt еlsеwhеrе - suсh аs thе US frоm Саdіllас аnd Lіnсоln. Мr Rоbеrtsоn wаs sреаkіng аt thе lаunсh еvеnt fоr thе sіх-суlіndеr fоur суlіndеr 640d Grаn Соuре, аhеаd оf іts UΚ арреаrаnсе nехt уеаr. Ingredients:

2 cups all-purpose  flour
1  teaspoon  baking soda
1 teaspoon  cream  of  tartar
1/4 teaspoon  salt
2 tablespoons sugar
1 cup buttermilk
1 egg, beaten
2 tablespoons butter, melted

Instructions:

1.  Preheat oven to 375 degrees F (190 degrees C).

2. In a large bowl,   combine flour, baking soda, cream of  tartar,   and salt.

3. In  a separate bowl, combine sugar, buttermilk, and egg.

4. Add the wet  ingredients to the dry ingredients and mix just  until combined.  Be careful not to overmix.

5. Pour the batter into  a greased 8-inch round pan.

6. Bake for 30-40  minutes, or until a toothpick inserted into the center  comes out clean.

7. Let the bread  cool in the pan for a few minutes,  then turn it out onto a wire rack to  cool  completely.

8. Serve warm with butter.

I'm feeling really lost and alone right now. I'm 37, have PCOS, and recently experienced my first miscarriage. It was my first pregnancy, and I was so excited to become a mom. My partner and I had been trying for a while, and we were overjoyed when we finally got the positive test result.

Everything seemed to be going well at first. I had some minor symptoms like nausea and fatigue, but nothing too severe. But then, around 8 weeks in, I started spotting. At first, it was light pink and didn't seem like much to worry about. But as the days went on, the bleeding became heavier and more frequent. I knew something wasn't right, but I tried to stay optimistic.

I went to my OBGYN and they did an ultrasound. The technician couldn't find a heartbeat, and my doctor told me that the baby hadn't developed properly. They said it was a missed abortion, which means the foetus stopped developing but my body didn't recognise it. I needed to have a D&C procedure to remove the tissue.

The procedure itself was quick and relatively painless, but emotionally, it was devastating. I felt like I had failed my baby and myself. My partner was amazing through all of this, but even his support couldn't take away the pain and sadness.

It's been a few weeks since the procedure, and I'm still struggling to come to terms with what happened. I feel guilty for not being able to carry my baby to term. I keep thinking about what I could have done differently, even though logically, I know there was nothing I could have done.

I'm also worried about trying again. What if it happens again? Can I handle another loss? I want to be a mother so badly, but I don't know if my body is capable of carrying a healthy pregnancy.

Has anyone else gone through something similar? Any words of encouragement or advice would be greatly appreciated.

Ingredients:
- 1 block of extra-firm tofu
- 2 tablespoons miso paste
- 1 tablespoon soy sauce
- 1 tablespoon maple syrup
- 1 tablespoon sesame oil
- 1 teaspoon garlic powder
- 1 teaspoon onion powder
- 1/2 teaspoon smoked paprika
- 1/2 teaspoon dried oregano
- Salt and pepper to taste

Instructions:

1. Drain the tofu and pat it dry with paper towels. Cut it into small cubes.

2. In a small bowl, whisk together the miso paste, soy sauce, maple syrup, sesame oil, garlic powder, onion powder, smoked paprika, oregano, salt, and pepper.

3. In a large skillet, heat a tablespoon of oil over medium-high heat. Add the tofu cubes and cook untill they are golden brown on all sides, about 5-7 minutes.

4. Remove the tofu from the skillet and add the miso mixture. Stir untill the sauce has thickened and coated the tofu, about 2-3 minutes.

5. Serve the vegetarian fake "meat" miso hot, over rice or noodles, topped with sliced scallions and sesame seeds. Enjoy!

Computing first extensions of modules is an important problem in the theory of graded Hecke algebras. In this paper, we study this problem for a class Of graded Hecke algebras that includes the algebras of type A, type B_r, and type C_r. We present a method for computing first extensions in these algebras, based On the notion of a graded division algebra with radical square zero. This method is then applied to compute first extensions between Modules of the algebras Of type A and type B_r.

3 bunches baby beets, washed, trimmed, and halved
1/3 cup extra-virgin olive oil
1 handful fresh thyme sprigs
Kosher salt and freshly ground black pepper
5 bunches arugula, washed, dried, and hand-torn
Celery leaves from 1 bunch celery, about 1/2 cup
1 cup walnut halves and pieces, toasted
1/2 pound blue cheese, crumbled
1 cup sour cream
2 tablespoons chopped fresh chives
1 lemon, juiced
Preheat the oven to 400 degrees F. Lay the beets on large sheet of aluminum foil, drizzle with oil, toss thyme on top, and season with salt and pepper. Fold up foil tightly to make sealed pouch and put it on a sheet pan. Bake until beets are tender when pierced, about 45 minutes to 1 hour. (Drop a knife in center of 1 beet; if it slides out without resistance, they're done.) Let the beets cool to room temperature and put them in a large mixing bowl. Add the arugula, celery leaves, and walnuts; toss to combine. To make blue cheese dressing: Put blue cheese and sour cream in a bowl, mashing with fork to combine. Add chives, lemon juice, and a few turns of freshly ground black pepper; mix to incorporate, leaving a few chunks of cheese in the dressing. Thin out the dressing with tablespoon of water, if you wish, to smooth out the consistency. Pour the blue cheese dressing over salad and toss gently to coat; season with salt and pepper. Put salad on a chilled platter and serve.

Ingredients:
2 cups whole wheat flour
1 tablespoon baking powder
1/2 teaspoon baking soda
1/4 teaspoon salt
1/4 cup cold butter
3/4 cup buttermilk
Instructions:
1. Preheat oven to 400 degrees F (200 degrees C).

2. In a large bowl, combine flour, baking powder, baking soda, and salt. Cut in butter until it resembles coarse crumbs. Stir in buttermilk until dough is moistened.

3. On a lightly floured surface, knead dough for 10 minutes. Roll out to 1/2 inch thickness. Cut with a biscuit cutter.

4. Place biscuits on a baking sheet. Bake for 12 minutes or until golden brown.

Ingredients:

1 (8 ounce) package fat-free cream cheese

1 cup fat-free sour  cream

1/2 cup sugar

1 teaspoon vanilla extract

2 eggs

1/3 cup unsweetened cocoa powder

1 (9  inch) prepared graham cracker crust

Directions:

1. Preheat  oven to  350 degrees F (175 degrees C).

2. In a large  bowl, combine  cream cheese,  sour cream, sugar, and vanilla.  Beat with an electric mixer until smooth. Add eggs and cocoa powder; mix well.  Pour  mixture  into  crust.

3. Bake   for 25 minutes. Cool before serving.
